n of a standard norm at the same time as European aspirations and ideas about post-socialist normalcy push many Bosnians to believe their country should have such a standard. The resulting tension is the space in which choice between standard variants takes on social meaning and contributes to emerging definitions of what it means to be Bosnian. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
Author = {Swagman, Kirstin J.},
Keywords = {language names, language norms, Bosnia, Herzegovina, Institutionalization, Language, Names, Social Norms},
School = {ProQuest Information & Learning},
Title = {Language names and norms in Bosnia and Herzegovina},
URL = {http://search.ebscohost.com.proxy.missouristate.edu/login.aspx?direct=true&db=psyh&AN=2012-99110-441&site=ehost-live&scope=site},
